03689nmm a2200577Ia 9780520920651DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209206517 a10.1525/97805209206512doi  a(DE-B1597)565711  a(OCoLC)1224277904  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBQ736b.F33 1998eb 7aREL0070002bisacsh04a294.3/097322104aThe Faces of Buddhism in America /ced. by Charles S. Prebish, Kenneth K. Tanaka.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (350 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBuddhism is the fastest growing religion in the United States, with adherents estimated in the several millions. But what exactly defines a "Buddhist"? This has been a much-debated question in recent years, particularly in regard to the religion's bifurcation into two camps: the so-called "imported" or ethnic Buddhism of Asian immigrants and the "convert" Buddhism of a mostly middle-class, liberal, intellectual elite. In this timely collection Charles S. Prebish and Kenneth K. Tanaka bring together some of the leading voices in Buddhist studies to examine the debates surrounding contemporary Buddhism's many faces.The contributors investigate newly Americanized Asian traditions such as Tibetan, Zen, Nichiren, Jodo Shinshu, and Theravada Buddhism and the changes they undergo to meet the expectations of a Western culture desperate for spiritual guidance. Race, feminism, homosexuality, psychology, environmentalism, and notions of authority are some of the issues confronting Buddhism for the first time in its three-thousand-year history and are powerfully addressed here.In recent years American Buddhism has been featured as a major story on ABC television news, National Public Radio, and in other national media. A strong new Buddhist journalism is emerging in the United States, and American Buddhism has made its way onto the Internet. The faces of Buddhism in America are diverse, active, and growing, and this book will be a valuable resource for anyone interested in understanding this vital religious movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBuddhismxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aBuddhismxUnited States. 0aBuddhismzUnited States. 4aBuddhism. 4aBuddhist studies. 4aTibet. 4areligion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh1 aPrebish, Charles S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTanaka, Kenneth K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520920651?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920651423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920651/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles